Although Kocik~\cite{Kocik2012} gives the geometric identification of Koide as a Descartes condition, to our knowledge the outer Soddy curvature $\mathcal{F}$ has not previously been computed and compared with hadronic observables. We discuss the relation of the present work to existing Koide-quark literature, in particular Rivero's algebraic ``waterfall''~\cite{Rivero2011} and the Rodejohann--Zhang quark Koide tuples~\cite{RodejohannZhang2011}, in Section~\ref{sec:notclaims}.

%======================================================================
\section{The outer Soddy curvature of the lepton triple}
%======================================================================

We have defined $\mathcal{F}$ in equation~(\ref{eq:F_alg}). Two further remarks before computing it.

\paragraph{The function $\mathcal{F}$ in Kocik's framework.}
$\mathcal{F}$ is not chosen from a catalog of symmetric polynomials. Once the Koide relation is read as a Descartes condition (Proposition~\ref{prop:koide_descartes}), the Descartes-determined quantities of dimension $[\text{mass}]^{1/2}$ are the two Soddy curvatures $k_4^{\pm} = e_1 \pm 2\sqrt{e_2}$. The choice between them is binary (inner versus outer), not a continuous selection. We adopt the outer curvature, the smaller of the two and the one corresponding to the larger circle in the Descartes configuration. This binary choice, along with the choice of integer power $n$ when comparing $\mathcal{F}^n$ to a quark mass and the choice of comparison quark, contributes to the look-elsewhere effect that we quantify explicitly in Section~\ref{sec:robustness}; the structural narrowing provided by Kocik's framework is real but partial, and we do not claim that $\mathcal{F}$ is the unique observable one could extract from the construction.

\paragraph{Numerical value.}
At the PDG~2024 central charged-lepton pole masses,
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F} \;=\; 9.7528\;\text{MeV}^{1/2}, \qquad \mathcal{F}^2 \;=\; 95.1134\;\text{MeV}.
\label{eq:F_value}
\end{equation}
The propagated uncertainty from PDG lepton inputs is $\sigma_{\mathcal{F}^2} = 0.010$~MeV (Section~\ref{sec:robustness}), dominated by the tau mass uncertainty. The corresponding geometric quantity $k_4^{\,-} = e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2} = 9.752607~\text{MeV}^{1/2}$ agrees with the algebraic $\mathcal{F} = 9.752823~\text{MeV}^{1/2}$ to one part in $10^5$, the precision at which Koide holds for the observed leptons. The corresponding difference in $\mathcal{F}^2$ is $0.004$~MeV. We emphasize that this is an approximation error (a systematic consequence of using $\mathcal{F}$ as a stand-in for the exact Soddy curvature when the observed leptons satisfy Koide only approximately), not a measurement uncertainty; the two should be tracked separately. Numerically, $0.004$~MeV is smaller than the lepton-side measurement uncertainty of $0.010$~MeV and very small compared to the lattice-side uncertainty of $0.814$~MeV that dominates the comparison, but its character is different. In what follows we use $\mathcal{F}$ throughout for analytic simplicity and report the comparison with $k_4^{\,-}$ once, here.

%======================================================================
\section{The observation}
%======================================================================

Evaluate the strange-quark $\msbar$ mass at the natural lepton-sum scale,
\begin{equation}
\mu_\star \;\equiv\; m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau \;=\; 1883.1\;\text{MeV},
\end{equation}
by running the FLAG~2024 lattice average~\cite{FLAG2024} $m_s^{\msbar}(2~\text{GeV}) = 93.5 \pm 0.8$~MeV (for $N_f = 2{+}1{+}1$) via four-loop QCD~\cite{CRunDec} with $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180$. This gives
\begin{equation}
m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star) \;=\; 95.132 \pm 0.814\;\text{MeV},
\end{equation}
where the uncertainty includes lattice input, the running of $\alpha_s$, charm-threshold matching, and four-loop truncation, with the lattice contribution dominating; we decompose this in Section~\ref{sec:robustness}. Both inputs are in the $\msbar$ scheme; the lattice average is the standard FLAG $\msbar$ result and we run it in $\msbar$. Comparing,
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F}^2 - m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star) \;=\; -0.019\;\text{MeV},
\label{eq:residual}
\end{equation}
or about $-0.023$ standard deviations of the lattice uncertainty. The PDG~2024 value $m_s^{\msbar}(2~\text{GeV}) = 93.5 \pm 0.8$~MeV gives a numerically identical result; the agreement does not depend on the choice between FLAG and PDG averaging.

We deliberately avoid framing~(\ref{eq:residual}) as a precision-significance claim. The residual is small in units of the lattice uncertainty, but the meaningful question is not how many standard deviations separate $\mathcal{F}^2$ from $m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$; it is how sharply the $\mathcal{F}^2 / m_s^{\msbar}$ match depends on the structural inputs that produced it. We address that question in Section~\ref{sec:robustness}.

\paragraph{Methodological note on order of operations.}
We disclose the order of operations leading to this observation, because it bears on the look-elsewhere assessment in Section~\ref{sec:robustness}. The author was investigating Kocik's geometric reading~\cite{Kocik2012} of the Koide relation and computed the fourth (outer Soddy) curvature of the Koide-saturating lepton triple as a geometric question, with the original motivation being whether the missing fourth curvature might admit a particle interpretation. The numerical agreement $\mathcal{F}^2 \approx m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$ was noticed only after the geometric computation was complete, on comparison with a previously consulted reference value for the strange-quark mass. The function $\mathcal{F}$ was therefore not selected from a class of candidate symmetric polynomials of lepton masses; it was determined by Kocik's framework. The choice of evaluation scale, however, deserves separate scrutiny: $\mu_\star = \sum m_\ell$ is the characteristic mass scale of the lepton triple in the same dimensional sense that $\mathcal{F}$ is the Descartes curvature, but it is not the only candidate. We address that selection freedom empirically in Section~\ref{sec:scale_alternatives}.

%======================================================================
\section{Robustness}
\label{sec:robustness}
%======================================================================

We report robustness checks across six axes: (i) propagation of input uncertainties and decomposition of the error budget, (ii) continuous scale sensitivity around $\mu_\star$, (iii) discrete alternative scale prescriptions, (iv) sensitivity of the $\mathcal{F}^2 / m_s^{\msbar}$ match to perturbations of the input lepton triple within the Koide manifold, (v) sensitivity of the perturbation analysis to the sampling prior, (vi) sensitivity across alternative quark species and integer powers, together with the sensitivity of (iv) and (vi) to the lower-cutoff filter on $\mu_\star$. These tests characterize how sharp the geometric construction is; they do not, and are not intended to, measure rarity or statistical significance. All computations are reproducible from the open-source code accompanying this paper~\cite{KoideSoddyCode}.

\subsection{Input sensitivity and error budget}

Propagating PDG~2024 lepton uncertainties through~(\ref{eq:F_alg}) yields $\sigma_{\mathcal{F}^2}^{\text{lepton}} = 0.010$~MeV, dominated by $\sigma_{m_\tau} = 0.09$~MeV. This is to be combined with the running uncertainty on $m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$. We decompose the latter by varying each input independently and re-running:
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lc}
\toprule
Source & $\sigma$ contribution (MeV) \\
\midrule
FLAG lattice $m_s(2~\text{GeV}) = 93.5 \pm 0.8$ & $0.814$ \\
$\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180 \pm 0.0009$ & $0.051$ \\
Charm threshold $m_c(m_c) = 1.273 \pm 0.005$~GeV & $0.000$ \\
Four-loop truncation (4L vs 3L) & $0.039$ \\
\midrule
Quadrature sum & $0.816$ \\
Reported total at $\mu_\star$ & $0.814$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
The quadrature sum agrees with the directly reported total to $0.002$~MeV, confirming that the uncertainty propagation is internally consistent and that the lattice input dominates by an order of magnitude over all other sources. Combined with the lepton-side budget, lepton inputs contribute approximately $0.02\%$ of the total error budget; the remaining $99.98\%$ comes from the lattice strange-quark mass. The lepton side of~(\ref{eq:residual}) is essentially exact at present precision.

\subsection{Continuous scale sensitivity}

We compute $m_s^{\msbar}(\mu)$ for $\mu/\mu_\star \in [0.5, 4.0]$ and compare against the constant $\mathcal{F}^2$. The agreement degrades monotonically away from $\mu_\star$, with residual reaching $-30\sigma$ at $\mu = 0.5\,\mu_\star$. The intervals over which $|\mathcal{F}^2 - m_s^{\msbar}(\mu)|$ remains within one and two standard deviations of $\sigma_{m_s}(\mu)$ are
\begin{align}
\text{1$\sigma$ window:} \quad &\mu \in [1845,\,1940]\;\text{MeV} \;\;\approx\;\mu_\star (1 \pm 2.5\%),\\
\text{2$\sigma$ window:} \quad &\mu \in [1789,\,1996]\;\text{MeV} \;\;\approx\;\mu_\star (1 \pm 5.5\%).
\end{align}
The 1$\sigma$ window is narrow (about $\pm 2.5\%$), confirming that the relation is picking out a specific scale rather than holding broadly across hadronic energies. Crucially, $\mu_\star = \sum m_\ell$ is exactly fixed by the lepton inputs, with no continuous adjustability: the agreement at $\mu_\star$ is not the result of choosing $\mu$ to optimize a fit, because $\mu_\star$ is determined by the same data ($m_e, m_\mu, m_\tau$) that determines $\mathcal{F}$.

\subsection{Alternative scale prescriptions}
\label{sec:scale_alternatives}

The continuous scan above shows that the relation is sharp at $\mu_\star$, but does not address whether $\mu_\star$ is the unique \emph{natural} scale among candidates derivable from lepton masses alone. We test eight alternative lepton-derived prescriptions, computing $m_s^{\msbar}(\mu)$ at each and comparing against the constant $\mathcal{F}^2 = 95.1134$~MeV:
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
Prescription & $\mu$ (MeV) & Match (within $1\sigma$)? \\
\midrule
$\mu_\star = m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau$ (baseline) & $1883.10$ & yes ($-0.02\sigma$) \\
$m_\mu + m_\tau$ & $1882.59$ & yes (trivially equivalent) \\
$m_\tau$ & $1776.93$ & no ($-2.0\sigma$) \\
$2~\text{GeV}$ (conventional reference, not lepton-derived) & $2000.00$ & no ($+2.0\sigma$) \\
$(m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau)/3$ & $\phantom{0}627.70$ & non-perturbative \\
$\sqrt{m_\mu m_\tau}$ & $\phantom{0}432.92$ & non-perturbative \\
$(m_e m_\mu m_\tau)^{1/3}$ & $\phantom{000}47.43$ & non-perturbative \\
$3/(1/m_e + 1/m_\mu + 1/m_\tau)$ (harmonic) & $\phantom{0000}1.53$ & non-perturbative \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
Of the four prescriptions in the perturbative regime ($\mu \gtrsim 1$~GeV), only $\sum m_\ell$ and the trivially equivalent $m_\mu + m_\tau$ produce matches. The next-best lepton-derived alternative ($m_\tau$ alone) misses by $-2.0\sigma$, and the conventional non-lepton reference scale of $2$~GeV misses by $+2.0\sigma$. Four further candidates fall below the perturbative regime and we report them as non-perturbative rather than excluding them. Within the perturbative regime, the match is specific to $\mu_\star = \sum m_\ell$; it is not generic across reasonable lepton-derived prescriptions.

\subsection{Sensitivity to Koide-manifold perturbation}
\label{sec:null_tight}

To characterize how sharply the $\mathcal{F}^2 / m_s^{\msbar}$ match depends on the specific input lepton triple, we perturb the triple within the Koide manifold and measure how often the match is preserved. This is a sensitivity statement about the geometric construction, not a hypothesis test against any physical null; the resulting fraction is a sharpness measure conditional on our chosen sampling family, and we make no claim that it measures rarity or improbability.

Sample candidate triples $(m_1, m_2, m_3)$ with $m_3$ drawn log-uniformly from $[10^0, 10^4]$~MeV, $m_1$ drawn log-uniformly from $[10^{-3}, 10^{-1}]\cdot m_3$, and $m_2$ solved analytically from the Koide condition $Q(m_1, m_2, m_3) = 2/3$ in the physical range $m_1 < m_2 < m_3$. Discard triples for which no real $m_2$ exists in this range. Verify $|Q - 2/3| < 10^{-5}$ for each retained triple. The sampling yields $25{,}485$ valid triples out of $10^5$ samples; the remaining samples were excluded because the natural scale $\mu_\star^{(i)} \equiv m_1 + m_2 + m_3$ fell below $1$~GeV, where four-loop QCD running is not reliable, so the test is undefined for those triples on methodological grounds rather than excluded post hoc. We verify in Section~\ref{sec:filter} that the result is stable when this cutoff is varied.

For each valid triple, compute $\mathcal{F}^{(i)}$ and $\mu_\star^{(i)}$, run $m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star^{(i)})$ from the FLAG 2~GeV input, and record the match as preserved if $|\mathcal{F}^{(i)\,2} - m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star^{(i)})| < \sigma_{m_s}(\mu_\star^{(i)})$. Of $25{,}485$ valid triples, $147$ preserved the match. The preservation rate is
\begin{equation}
p_{\text{match}} \;=\; 0.5768\%, \qquad
95\%\text{ Clopper--Pearson interval (sampling noise only):}\;[0.49\%,\,0.68\%].
\label{eq:tight_null}
\end{equation}
The interval quantifies binomial sampling uncertainty in the Monte Carlo only; it does not capture model-specification uncertainty from the choice of prior, which we address separately in Section~\ref{sec:prior_sensitivity}. The distribution of $(\mathcal{F}^{(i)\,2} - m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star^{(i)}))/\sigma_{m_s}$ across the $25{,}485$ valid samples spans roughly $\pm 50$ standard deviations; the observed lepton triple sits within the central $\pm 1\sigma$ window, which is the outcome quantified by~(\ref{eq:tight_null}). The smallness of $p_{\text{match}}$ measures how sharply the geometric construction selects the observed triple from nearby Koide-saturating alternatives, not the probability of the match arising by chance under any physical model.

\subsection{Prior sensitivity}
\label{sec:prior_sensitivity}

The preservation rate~(\ref{eq:tight_null}) depends on the choice of sampling family over Koide-saturating triples. The log-uniform prior used above is one reasonable choice but not the only one. We re-run the sensitivity analysis under three additional sampling priors selected to span the space of reasonable alternatives:
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
Prior & Preservation rate & 95\% CI \\
\midrule
A: log-uniform $m_3 \in [10^0, 10^4]$~MeV (baseline) & $0.58\%$ & $[0.49,\,0.68]$ \\
B: log-uniform $m_3 \in [10^{-1}, 10^5]$~MeV (wider range) & $0.37\%$ & $[0.31,\,0.45]$ \\
C: log-uniform $m_1/m_3 \in [10^{-4}, 10^{-2}]$ (smaller ratio) & $0.56\%$ & $[0.47,\,0.66]$ \\
D: linear-uniform on $m_3$ and $m_1/m_3$ (stress test) & $0.26\%$ & $[0.23,\,0.30]$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
All four sampling priors give preservation rates in the range $0.26\%$--$0.58\%$, with maximum-to-minimum fold variation of $2.2$. The deliberately adversarial linear prior (D), which heavily weights heavy triples and is not characteristic of mass-hierarchy problems, lowers the preservation rate rather than raising it. No sampling prior we tested raises the preservation rate above $1\%$. The factor-of-two fold variation is itself informative: it shows that the preservation rate is a sharpness diagnostic of the geometric construction modulated by the sampling family, not a unique property of either, and any reader weighting the magnitude of $p_{\text{match}}$ should weight it by their credibility in the sampling family used.

\subsection{Sensitivity across quark species, integer powers, and filter cutoff}
\label{sec:filter}

To characterize sensitivity across the broader space of possible lepton-derived to quark-mass matchings, we compute $\mathcal{F}^n$ for $n \in \{1, 2, 3\}$ and compare against each of $\{m_u, m_d, m_s, m_c, m_b\}$ at the natural scale $\mu_\star^{(i)}$ of each triple, recording a triple as preserving any match if any of the $15$ comparisons agrees within current lattice $1\sigma$. This characterizes the residual selection freedom in the choice of comparison observable, beyond the choice of input triple already addressed in Section~\ref{sec:null_tight}. Across the same $25{,}485$ valid triples, the overall preservation rate is
\begin{equation}
p_{\text{any}} \;=\; 0.812\%, \qquad
95\%\text{ Clopper--Pearson interval (sampling noise only):}\;[0.71\%,\,0.93\%],
\label{eq:loose_null}
\end{equation}
only marginally larger than $p_{\text{match}}$. The breakdown by quark and integer power is shown in Table~\ref{tab:loose}. Up- and down-quark matches at $n = 1$ are physically excluded by mass dimension ($\mathcal{F}^1 \sim 10$~MeV is too large for $m_u, m_d$). Strange matches at $n = 2$ dominate, accounting for $147/207 \approx 71\%$ of all preserved matches in this broader sensitivity test. Charm matches at $n = 3$ and bottom matches at $n = 3$ exist for some triples in the sampling, but the observed lepton triple is not among them.

